[00:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'multi- character lip sync. It\'s a really big deal and today is an exciting day because I\'m going to introduce you to a tool by Voso. It\'s the first one I\'ve come across where they\'ve actually attempted to crack that problem. Now, I need you to understand why it\'s such a'

[00:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'big deal for me. I\'m a narrative filmmaker. I\'m on a quest, if you don\'t already know, to take a screenplay that I wrote that I love. It took me more than 10 years to write it, and I\'m on a long-term quest to turn it into a watchable demo movie using emerging AI'

[00:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tools. I have a list of um it\'s pushing 20 items. I think there\'s 18 at the moment. Things that I need an AI tool to do if I have half a chance of being able to create narrative film and television'

[00:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'content. And number 17 on that list is multicaracter lips sync. So, in this video, I\'m going to introduce you to Voso\'s new multi character lip-sync tool. And uh this is a sponsored video.'

[00:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I wasn\'t going to do any more sponsor videos, but I worked with Voso last year to introduce their lips sync and dubbing tool, and it\'s actually really good. It\'s so funny. Lip syncing is what'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'they do, so it\'s a specialist area for them. This is their first version, and it\'s going to get better. So, before we get into this, there are some things that you need to know. First, when it comes to narrative film and television,'

[01:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'most shots don\'t require more than two, maybe three people max in the same shot speaking at the same time. Most shots, uh, even with groups, they cut to the'

[01:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'individual speaking very quickly, so you can focus on just them. And there may be another person in there, but it\'s very unusual to have a shot where you\'ve got a single shot with multiple people who are all speaking at different times. I'

[01:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'run my tests along the idea of a a gang of villains gathered around a table discussing how they were going to pull off this heist and some of the obstacles they were facing. So, it\'s unusual that you need these kind of shots, but when'

[01:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you do need multi- character lip sync, you really need it and it\'s a pain if you don\'t have a tool that will do it. Now, we need to talk about five things that good lip sync needs if it\'s going to pull it off successfully. So the'

[02:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'first thing is you need a big face in the frame ideally so that the AI has a really clear view of the mouth. Second thing is you need really clear lighting. The third thing is ideally you would have small movements. In fact, if'

[02:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'there\'s no movement at all, that makes it even easier for the AI tool. So any AI tool that is attempting to track movement, it\'s ambitious and it\'s to be applauded. The next thing is dark skin tones. Now, dark skin tones in cinema already have to be treated with extra'

[02:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'care when it comes to lighting. Particularly in dramatic, gritty, dark kind of shots, you already have lots of darkness in the shot. And so, if you\'ve got dark skin tones mixed in with lots of shadows, you have to go to extra'

[02:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'efforts to light the faces carefully. The other thing you need is sharp focus. Ideally, if you\'ve got a character who\'s blurry, lip-sync struggles to to kind of really replicate the blurriness and be able to pick out the face. Now, with all'

[03:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of that said, here\'s one of the catches with multicar lip sync. If you have multiple characters in a shot who are speaking, by default, you have lots of people and you don\'t have a close-up'

[03:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'shot. You\'ve typically got a wide shot, at the very least, a very tightly packed medium shot, but usually it\'s a wide shot. And what that means is the more people you have in the frame, the smaller each head becomes and the smaller each mouth becomes, which means'

[03:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that the AI has less and less material to work with, and it makes it harder to pull off natural and authentic looking lip sync. So that\'s something just to be aware of. So what VZO have done here is a really ambitious and really brilliant'

[03:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'attempt at trying to crack that. By the way, if you have a task that requires multiple characters in the shot, they have a free version. So go and try it out. So let me tell you how I set up this particular shot. I created the'

[03:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'original image in midjourney. Then I pulled it into cling to animate it. And I prompted for some kind of animation, some kind of discussion around a table and the characters pointing at the contents of the table as if they were'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'planning their heist. I then scripted something around the movements that each character was uh was pulling off. So I thought I\'d try and at least make the script match the movements. So, I went into 11 Labs to create the script and I'

[04:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'chose voices that were deliberately quite different. And then I pulled the video from Cling into Final Cut Pro. And then I pulled all the audio lines from 11 Labs into Final Cut Pro. I lined them up and I chopped them up and I I created this alligators. Alligators. Alligators'

[04:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'here in Snakes. They It had to be alligators. Why not fluffy bunnies? Just one time. Now, you\'ll see there\'s no lip sync there, but you can kind of see what\'s going on. And again, it should be'

[04:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'noted that the reason I use different voices is to give the AI tool some hope of being able to tell the difference between who\'s speaking. So when you first come into the tool, you\'ve got the option to generate a talking video. And'

[05:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I went and clicked on that one. And you\'ve got these two options to start with a video or start with a photo. So I imported the video that I had already created in Final Cut Pro. And again, this version had audio already baked'

[05:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'into the video. So the tool was going to use that as its underpinning audio. And so you see when you import it, you\'ve got the option to create audio from three sources. You can type out text to create the audio. You can import an'

[05:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'audio file separately. Or you can use the audio that\'s already baked into the video that you\'ve imported. In my case, that\'s what I did. There\'s even with this model the latitude to have faces that are sideways on which is a'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'notoriously difficult thing for AI to attempt to do when it comes to lip syncing. So the next step in the process is to either select one face so that the uh you can then go and choose which face'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is the face that you want to be speaking or you have auto detect and auto detect can work with up to six faces. This is extraordinary up to six faces in a shot. Mine typically had no more than four and'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that was enough to to run this test. So when you click the auto detect, it takes a few minutes and then it comes back to confirm that these are the faces that it has found that it thinks are ready for lip sync. And if there are some in there'

[06:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that you don\'t want, you can deselect them again. Notice the guy with the side on view. Very, very impressive that they\'ve picked that out and they\'re saying we\'re going to give this guy a go. This guy that you can hardly see back here. It\'s good. So the next part of the process takes it takes about an'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'hour. I won\'t lie. This is not a fast process at the moment. I\'m sure it\'ll get quicker. Um, but you it\'s off. Now, when it comes back that it\'s almost always wrong. I\'ll level with you'

[06:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'because the AI doesn\'t know really who to assign which voice to. But what it does do is it has a crack at figuring out where one voice ends and another voice begins. And so, you\'ll see that'

[06:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'down here on the timeline. You can see the the clip is broken up into little sections. And that\'s the AI guessing that this is a different character. And each little section is assigned to a face on the screen. So there are really'

[07:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'two editing things that you need to do at this point. One is to look through the video clip at the bottom. And if you\'ve got a section where two people are speaking within the same clip, then you\'ve got this slicing tool over here'

[07:24] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that will let you just go and separate um a clip into two so that the AI knows that these are two distinctly separate characters speaking. And then you\'ve got the option to either deselect the current selection, which is usually what'

[07:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you have to do, and then select the one that you actually want to be delivering that line. And then you go through your clip section by section by section, assigning each section to the face that you want to be delivering that audio.'

[07:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'And by the way, this part is free. So you don\'t get charged for re-editing this. And to redo it only actually takes a few minutes after this, which is surprising given that it takes more than an hour for the first thing to to get done. But the the second version, nice'

[08:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and quick, just a few minutes. So, at the end of that, you\'re left with this. Alligators. Alligators. Alligators here and snakes there. It had to be alligators. Why not fluffy bunnies? Just'

[08:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one time. Alligators. Alligators. Alligators here and snakes there. It had to be alligators. Why not fluffy bunnies? Just one time. So, the results'

[08:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'come back and I\'ll be honest, it hasn\'t done a bad job. It hasn\'t done the perfect job, but it\'s not a disaster. To say that this is a first attempt is incredibly important and incredibly'

[08:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'impressive. If you have a project that you\'re working on and you\'re really struggling with multi- character lip sync, this is worth checking out to see if it can crack your problem. So, here\'s some others that I tried just to try out some different characters. We could use'

[08:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'dynamite. So, who brought the keys? I thought you brought the keys. I ain\'t got no keys. This is ridiculous. We could use dynamite. So, who brought the'

[09:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'keys? I thought you brought the keys. I ain\'t got no key. This is ridiculous. One of the things to point out is that if your underlying video that CL, in my case, Clling has created has some blurry'

[09:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'faces or has some blurry hands. Of course, this tool isn\'t going to do anything about that and you can still end up with problems. By the way, if you live anywhere near London and you feel like having a meet up face to face, uh'

[09:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'next week, next Tuesday, 17th of June, um I\'m going to an AI networking meetup in London at ITV Studios. Uh they\'ve still got seats available. The seats are free. Like, so it\'s free to come along for the evening. Um you know, 7 to 9'

[09:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'kind of time and drinks afterwards for anybody who wants to stick around. So, if you happen to be in the area and you feel like meeting up face to face, come say hi. Uh I\'ll put a link below. I think they still have some tickets left,'

[09:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so just jump on one quick while you can grab them. Should be a good evening. They get some good speakers and um it\'s it\'s really about networking for the AI film making community around London. It\'s finally here. Multi-person lipsync. So, we should probably show you how the'

[10:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'magic happens. It\'s finally here. Multi-person lipsync. So, we should probably show you how the magic happens. It\'s finally here.'

[10:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Multi-person lips sync. So, we should probably show you how the magic happens. So, well done, Vos. Thank you very much for introducing multicar lipsync. I can'

[10:33] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'now not just check that off my list, but I can put VZO\'s name firmly next to uh multi character lip-sync on my list of requirements for a cinematic uh film'

